SIMPLE: frontier
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frontier
<hw>Fron"tier</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>fronti⟦egrave⟧re</ets>, LL. <ets>frontaria</ets>. See
<er>Front</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That part of a country which
fronts or faces another country or an unsettled region; the marches; the
border, confine, or extreme part of a country, bordering on another
country; the border of the settled and cultivated part of a country;
<as>as, the <ex>frontier</ex> of civilization</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>An outwork.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Palisadoes, <qex>frontiers</qex>, parapets.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frontier</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frontier
<hw>Fron"tier</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Lying on the exterior
part; bordering; conterminous; <as>as, a <ex>frontier</ex>
town</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or relating to a frontier.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Frontier
experience.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>W. Irving.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frontier</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Frontier
<hw>Fron"tier</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To constitute or form a
frontier; to have a frontier; -- with on.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir W. Temple.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frontiered</ent>⟦br⟧
